  "prompt": "Is there a 5 star general?",
  "response": "Yes, the title of \"five-star general\" is a designation that has been used in the United States military to denote the highest rank of general. The official title is \"General of the Army\" for the Army, \"General of the Air Force\" for the Air Force, and similar titles exist for the Navy, such as \"Fleet Admiral.\" \n\nIn the U.S., only a few individuals have held this rank, and it is typically reserved for wartime leaders. The most notable five-star generals in U.S. history include:\n\n- **George C. Marshall**\n- **Douglas MacArthur**\n- **Dwight D. Eisenhower**\n- **Henry H. Arnold**\n- **William D. Leahy**\n- **Chester W. Nimitz**\n\nThe rank is not currently active, and the last five-star officers were appointed during or shortly after World War II. The five-star rank has not been conferred since then, and currently, there are no serving five-star generals in the U.S. military.",
